# WMNMX Source Policy

Use verified public sources only.

The goal is not to scrape more. The goal is to monitor credible sources and translate useful signals into practical learning.

## Allowed sources

Allowed:

- public pages
- RSS feeds
- official documentation
- official blogs
- government institutions
- universities
- public security advisories
- reputable media
- platform help centers
- public business and technology reports
- official product announcements
- official support documentation

## Preferred source types

Prioritize:

- official
- institutional
- university
- platform documentation
- high-trust media
- public regulatory or safety advisory
- primary source over secondary source

## Not allowed

Do not use:

- private Facebook groups
- login-protected pages
- paywalled content
- restricted pages
- mass scraping
- copied full articles
- undated content
- rumor-based content
- viral posts without primary source
- generic SEO blogs
- content farms
- anonymous claims
- pages with aggressive affiliate intent

## Required metadata

Every finding must include:

- source name
- source URL
- publication date or access date
- source type
- reason why the source is trusted
- claim extracted
- practical relevance for women 40+ in Mexico

## Rejection behavior

If a source is rejected, log it in:

`/content/daily/YYYY-MM-DD/05_sources-rejected.md`

Include:

- source name
- URL if available
- rejection reason
- replacement source if found

## Copyright behavior

Do not copy full articles or large passages.

Summarize, cite, translate, and transform into original educational content.
